solutions.content:
**Based on the approach of the problem  "Allocating minimum number of pages."**
* Consider the question as given an array,which is an array of different books at ith index with values as the no. of pages in ith book 
```
arr[]: 10 20 30 40
and k=2 children(suppose).
```
* Now think you want to allocate books to each of the "k" student such that the burden on every student can be minimized;
Since k=2,
if we partition arr as 

```
arr1[]= 10 
arr2[] = 20 30 40 
```
the second student would have to read , ```20+30+40=90  ```
which is not optimal.
* What if we divide the arr as :
```
arr1[]= 10 20
arr2[] = 30 40 
```
so the **max** pages to be read by either student would be ```30+40=70```
* Can we further optimize it? Let's split the arr as :
```
arr1[]= 10 20 30
arr2[] = 40 
```
Now the **max** pages to be read by either student would be ```10+20+30=60```
which is our optimal answer.

**Now how do we implement this logic using Binary Search for the Question 410. Split Array Largest Sum?**
Input:
nums = [7,2,5,10,8]
m = 2

1. At any point, the partition sum can we in the range [0,sum of all array elements]
2. The range can be represented as :
	```
	int low=0;
	int high =sum; //(sum is the cumulative sum of all elements in "nums")
	```
3. We calculate *mid* for the range to see if we can partition the array in *k* continous subarrays whose sum is not more than mid.
```
int mid =low+(high-low)/2;
```

4. To check if this value of mid can we a valid answer we create a function named isValid().
*  Validiy of *mid* means , we need to determine if we need k partitions for this max sum or more.
*  To check that we traverse the whole array *nums* keep on adding values in *sum* such that,
```
for( int i : nums ){
	sum+=i;
```
* If at any point the cumulative sum exceeds our value of *mid* (which is supposed to be the max sum of this partition),  and we need more than *k* partitions to accumulate it, we return false;
e.g. if mid =10
nums[] = 1 6 3 9 15 4
k=2
we wouldn't be able to create exactly 2 subarrays with their max sum = 10(mid).
So we return false.
5. We then check for a higher value if we fail.
```
low=mid+1;
```

6. Even if we find a value of *mid* that doesn't voilate the validity of partitioning the array, we still try to get a lower value.
```
if (isValid){
	res=min(res,mid);
	high=mid-1;//we still check for a lower value than mid.
```
[Book allocation problem Link](http:https://www.***.org/allocate-minimum-number-pages///)

Took me a lot of time to write up this, if it helps you i'll be glad.

**Below is the implementation of above logic.**

```
class Solution {
public:
    int splitArray(vector<int>& nums, int m) {
        int n=size(nums); 
        long long  sum=0;
        for(long long  i : nums){
            if (i==INT_MAX)
                return INT_MAX; //Even if you do n partitions you won't be able to reduce this, so simply this will be the max sum.
            sum+=i;
        }
        if (m==1) //if you can't partition it then the max value in the whole array will be the max sum.
            return sum;
        long long low=0;
        long high=sum; // "high" denotes the maximum sum that is an possible answer.
        long long  mid;
        long long  res=INT_MAX;
        while (low<=high){
            mid=low+(high-low)/2;
            if (isValid(nums,n,m,mid)) //"isvalid()" is to check if this value , "mid" can be a valid answer for m partitions.
            {
                res=min(res,mid);
                high=mid-1; //even when we find an answer we check for a lesser value;
            }
            else 
                low=mid+1;

        }
        return res;
    }

    bool isValid(vector<int> nums,int n, int m, int mid){
        int assn=1; //assignments=1 initially , means can we allocate the values to 1 partition only without violating the condition of having sum <=mid;
        int sum=0;
        for(int i : nums){
            sum+=i;
            if (sum>mid){
                assn++;
                sum=i;
                if (sum>mid) //if at any instance we find that this value is greater than current max sum we are checking for we return false;
                    return false;
            }
            if (assn>m) //if we need more than required partitions for the current max ("mid") value we are checking for we return false;
                return false;
        }
        return true; // if everything is fine without violating any condition we return true;
    }
};
```

