solutions.content:
**Solution 1:** Derived from the DP solution given under the solution tab for this question on leetcode. So we use a 2D DP, where dp[i][j] the max sum until ith number, with j partitions (Remember here we talking about numbers (start from 1) and not indexes, hence dp[0][0] = 0). Now, if there is some value k<i, then dp[i][j] = min(dp[i][j], max(dp[k][j-1], sum of elements in range k to i)).
Meaning for until kth number with j-1 partitions, whatever as the maximum, and compare it to the sum of elements between k and i. Update the dp (use the value) that gives us minimum sum.
```
class Solution {
public:
    int splitArray(vector<int>& nums, int m) {
        int n = nums.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n+1, vector<int>(m+1, INT_MAX));
        dp[0][0] = 0;
        vector<int> prefix(n+1, 0);
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
        {
            prefix[i+1] = prefix[i] + nums[i];
        }
        for(int i=1; i<=n; i++)
        {
            for(int j=1; j<=m; j++)
            {
                for(int k=0; k<i; k++)
                {
                    dp[i][j] = min(dp[i][j], max(dp[k][j-1], prefix[i]-prefix[k]));
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[n][m];
    }
};
```
Time complexity: O(n^2 * m)
Space complexity: O(n * m)

**Solution 2:** This is the solution that is the fast implemention. Basically imagine an l and r value between which the maximum sum of subarray exists. Now we need to split the array such that this maximum sum is minimised. 
Now, if we split array at some point, and maximum sum of subarray is some value x, we go on to find find if there exists another value between range [l, x) (less than x) for same condition, i.e. if there exists x_0 (<x) that corresponds to maximum sum of subarrray while dividing in another way.
So, first set the l and r values to maximum element in array and sum of all elements in the array.
Now, do a binary search on this range (mid = (left+right)/2)and while doing so, traverse whole array and split the array in such a way that no subarray sum goes > mid. 
If at any point, the current sum goes >mid. Then start sum of subarray from nums[i] and increment the count of partitions.
Atlast check if the count of partitions is <= m (the number of partitions given in input). If it is so (maximum sum is less than mid with partitions <= m) then we compare the mid with ans and update it. Also we update r = mid-1. As now we need to find it on left side range.
If not, then we need to find in the RHS range and set l  = mid+1.
```
class Solution {
public:
    int splitArray(vector<int>& nums, int m) {
        long l = 0, r = 0;
        int n = nums.size();
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
        {
            r+=nums[i];
            if(l<nums[i])
                l =nums[i];
        } //left value will be a single largest element and r value will be sum of all elements
        //all elements in one subarray
        long ans = r;
        while(l<=r)
        {
            long mid = (long)(l+r)/2;
            long sum = 0;
            int count = 1;
            for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
            {
                if(sum+nums[i]>mid)
                {
                    count++;
                    sum = nums[i];
                }
                else
                    sum+=nums[i];
            }
            if(count<=m)
            {
                ans = min(ans, mid);
                r = mid-1;
            }
            else
                l = mid+1;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
Time complexity : O(n * log(sum_of_array))
Space complexity: O(1)

