solutions.content:
We can first restrict the search space to **[max(nums), sum(nums)]**, the lower bound `max(nums)` means the biggest one is grouped solely and the upper bound `sum(nums)` means there is only one group. 

To search in a consecutive range, we can easily think of Binary Search to decrease search space. The valid condition in this problem is almost the same as LC1011, which is whether we can seperate this array into m groups and each group's sum is no larger than current value. 

Since the subarray should be continuous, it is much easier. We can simply calculate how much groups we need and compare it to m.

**Time Complexity**: O(n log(sum(nums))), where n is the length of nums[].
**Space Complexity**: O(1)

Similar to: LC1011

```
class Solution {
    public int splitArray(int[] nums, int m) {
        //range[max(nums), sum(nums)]
        int lo = 0, hi = 0;
        for(int num: nums){
            if(num > lo){
                lo = num;
            }
            hi += num;
        }
        while (lo <= hi){
            int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;
            if(mIsValid(nums, m, mid)){
                hi = mid - 1;
            }else{
                lo = mid + 1;
            }
        }
        return lo;
    }

    private boolean mIsValid(int[] nums, int m, int val){
        //if group into m groups, each group's sum <= val
        int groupNeed = 0, curSum = 0;
        for(int num: nums){
            curSum += num;
            if(curSum > val){
                ++groupNeed;
                curSum = num;
            }
        }
        if(curSum > 0){
            ++groupNeed;
        }
        return groupNeed <= m;
    }
}
```

