solutions.content:
**1. backtrak + memo + presum**

Firstly, in such 'cut down into regions' problems, we could always use backtrack (dfs) method, which enable us to search every possible solution.

Here, I additionally leverage memo and presum techniques to make the search process faster. But ultimatly, the time usage is still quiet a lot. (40ms)

```
class Solution {
    int[] presum;
    int[][] dp;
    int n,cuts;
    public int splitArray(int[] nums, int m) {
        n = nums.length;
        cuts = m-1;
        dp = new int[n][cuts+1];
        presum = new int[n+1];
        for (int i=1;i<=n;i++) presum[i] = nums[i-1]+presum[i-1];
        return dfs(0,presum,cuts);
    }

    int dfs(int pos, int[] presum, int cut){
        if (cut==0) return presum[n]-presum[pos];
        if (dp[pos][cut]!=0) return dp[pos][cut];
        int curmax = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int i=pos+1; i<n && cut<=n-i;i++){
            curmax = Math.min(curmax, Math.max(presum[i]-presum[pos],
                              dfs(i, presum, cut-1)));
        }
        dp[pos][cut] = curmax;
        return curmax;
    }
}
```

**2. bottom-up dp**

Also, when there is a top-down dfs, there would be a bottom-up method. 
And the time is reduced for a half. (20ms)

```
class Solution {
    int n;
    int[] presum;
    int[][] dp;
    public int splitArray(int[] nums, int m) {
        n = nums.length;
        dp = new int[m][n];
        presum = new int[n+1];
        for (int i=1;i<=n;i++) presum[i] = nums[i-1]+presum[i-1];
        for (int ord=0; ord<m; ord++){
            int curmax = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
            for (int tail=ord; tail<n-(m-1-ord); tail++){
                for (int pre=ord; pre<=tail; pre++){
                    if (ord==0) {
                        curmax = presum[tail+1];
                        continue;
                    }
                    curmax = Math.min(curmax, Math.max(
                      presum[tail+1]-presum[pre],dp[ord-1][pre-1]));
                }
                dp[ord][tail] = curmax;
                curmax = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
            }
        }
        return dp[m-1][n-1];
    }
}
```


**3. Trial and Error**
The  above  solutions take nearly O(N^3) time complexity to solve the problem.
But by leveraging the binary search tool in trial and error, the time could be reduced to O(NlogN).

The main goal is to test every possible min sum (which is in the rage [max, sum] for correctness), and in every test step, we use a trial process to determine whether the current min sum is valid or not.

```
class Solution {
    public int splitArray(int[] nums, int m) {
        int low=0, high=0, mid, cnt;
        for (int i: nums){
            low = Math.max(low, i);
            high = i>Integer.MAX_VALUE-high?Integer.MAX_VALUE:high+i;
        }
        while (low < high){
            mid = low + (high-low)/2;
            cnt = trial(nums, mid);
            if (cnt>m){
                low = mid+1;
            }else if (cnt<m){
                high = mid-1;
            }else{
                high = mid;
            }
        }
        return low;
    }

    int trial(int[] nums, int k){
        int cnt=1, cursum=0;
        for (int i:nums){
            cursum += i;
            if (cursum>k){
                cursum=i;
                cnt++;
            }
        }
        return cnt;
    }
}
```

