# 2.Binary Search: O(n) check
when we seen such a description that "minimize the largest xxx", we should always think about binary search. In this problem, apparently the result would be monotonic, because if a smaller result can work, the greater result should work too, because we can always add more element to the subarray which has the largest sum to make it greater than before.

idea: check the range from max number of the array to the sum of the array. and every check will cost O(n), because we will check the whole array every time.

**time**: O(log(sum)*n), space: O(1)

```
class Solution {
    public int splitArray(int[] nums, int m) {
        int maxNumber = 0, arraySum = 0;
        for (int i : nums) {
            maxNumber = Math.max(maxNumber, i);
            arraySum += i;
        }
        int l = maxNumber, r = arraySum;
        while (l < r) {
            int mid = l + (r - l) / 2;
            if (check(nums, m, mid))
                r = mid;
            else // if not satisfied, then mid is too small, we need enlarge our l
                l = mid + 1;
        }
        return l;
    }
    /**
     * check if satisfied, cost O(n)
     */
    private boolean check(int[] nums, int m, int s) {
        int i = 0, k = 0;
        while (i < nums.length && k < m) {
            int sum = 0;
            while (i < nums.length && sum + nums[i] <= s)
                sum += nums[i++];
            k++;
        }
        return i == nums.length;
    }
}
```

