# 3.Binary Search: O(mlog(n)) check
**Follow up**: now think about the question, "what if n is much greater than m"
Don't forget the prefixSum is also a monotonic array, because the array consists of non-negative integers. So, we can also use binary search to check if the result is satisfied.

**time**: O(log(sum)\*m*log(n)), space: O(n)
```
class Solution {
    public int splitArray(int[] nums, int m) {
        int[] prefixSum = new int[nums.length + 1];
        int maxNumber = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            maxNumber = Math.max(maxNumber, nums[i]);
            prefixSum[i+1] = prefixSum[i] + nums[i];
        }
        int l = maxNumber, r = prefixSum[nums.length];
        while (l < r) {
            int mid = l + (r - l) / 2;
            if (check(prefixSum, m, mid))
                r = mid;
            else // if not satisfied, then mid is too small, we need enlarge our l
                l = mid + 1;
        }
        return l;
    }
    /**
     * this check cost O(mlog(n))
     */
    private boolean check(int[] prefixSum, int m, int s) {
        int i = 1, k = 0;
        while (i < prefixSum.length && k < m) {
            i = getIndex(prefixSum, i, prefixSum[i-1] + s);
            k++;
        }
        return i == prefixSum.length;
    }
    /**
     * return the smallest index+1(next index) such that the sum of subarray is greater than s
     */
    private int getIndex(int[] prefixSum, int i, int s) {
        int l = i, r = prefixSum.length;
        while (l < r) {
            int m = l + (r - l) / 2;
            // we want to find the smallest greater than s
            if (prefixSum[m] > s)
                r = m;
            else
                l = m + 1;
        }
        // l is the next index
        return l;
    }
}
```
